    base:desc "GreenhouseDT adopts an ad‑hoc microservice architecture, where the digital twin logic and the data collection pipeline are hosted on a set of virtual machines. Within each VM, distinct components—the InfluxDB time‑series database, an ActiveMQ broker, and a data ingestion service—are launched as separate processes. Communication between the greenhouse physical plant and the twin is carried out via ActiveMQ topics that carry sensor readings cast into JSON messages. The ingestion service subscribes to these topics, writes the data to InfluxDB, and triggers the behavioral adaptation logic that times the greenhouse control loops. The entire stack is bootstrapped using a simple shell script that pulls the VM images, installs the required packages, and starts the services in order. Resource constraints are enforced at the VM level (e.g., 2 vCPU, 4 GiB RAM per VM), and each component uses a dedicated port to avoid conflicts. Because the exemplar is intentionally ad‑hoc, there is no central orchestrator beyond the VM bootstrap script, and all coordination is via the publish/subscribe mechanism provided by ActiveMQ."
]

